1. Introduction

Long QT syndrome (LQTS) is characterized by prolongation of the
cardiac action potential, syncopal attacks, torsades de pointes arrhyth-
mias and sudden cardiac death [1–3]. The slow component of delayed
rectiﬁer K+ current (IKs) in the heart modulates repolarization of cardiac
action potential. The IKs channel is formed by the co-assembly of KCNQ1
α-subunits and KCNE1 β-subunits [4,5]. Mutations in the KCNQ1 cause
the most frequent form of inherited LQT1 [6]. Exercise-related cardiac
events dominate the clinical picture of LQT1 patients.

Pre-mRNA processing is an important aspect of gene expression
and consists of the precise recognition of exons and removal of introns
in such a way that the exons are joined to form mature mRNAs with
intact translational reading frames [7,8]. Disruption of normal splicing
as a result of genetic mutation can lead to the generation of abnormal

